{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658538","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658538"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:51:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:51:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20773"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20773","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20773"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.05,0.05,0.76,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13648"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95896"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13648","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13648"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20773"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78646"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11582"},{"type":"tags","id":"11753"},{"type":"tags","id":"12624"},{"type":"tags","id":"12625"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32846"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32847"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95896","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/95896"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man has bronze-coloured skin, diabetes, and hepatomegaly. Liver biopsy shows golden-brown granular deposits within hepatocytes that stain positively with Prussian blue.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the pigment observed in this patient\u0027s liver tissue?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["A bilirubin-derived pigment from cholestasis","A melanin-derived pigment from skin cells","A lipofuscin pigment from cellular aging","An iron-containing pigment from ferritin aggregates","A carbon-containing pigment from environmental exposure"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe golden-brown granular deposits that stain positively with Prussian blue represent hemosiderin, which is \u003Cstrong\u003Ean iron-containing pigment from ferritin aggregates\u003C/strong\u003E. Hemosiderin is a hemoglobin-derived pigment that forms when there is excess iron in the body. It represents aggregates of ferritin micelles and is one of the major storage forms of iron.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation of bronze skin, diabetes, and hepatomegaly is classic for hemochromatosis, a condition of systemic iron overload that leads to hemosiderosis (deposition of hemosiderin) in multiple organs. Prussian blue is a histochemical stain specific for iron, confirming the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA bilirubin-derived pigment from cholestasis\u003C/strong\u003E - Bilirubin pigment appears green-yellow and does not stain with Prussian blue. While it is also derived from hemoglobin breakdown, it represents the non-iron portion of heme.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA melanin-derived pigment from skin cells\u003C/strong\u003E - Melanin is brown-black but is not typically found in liver tissue and does not stain with Prussian blue.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA lipofuscin pigment from cellular aging\u003C/strong\u003E - Lipofuscin is a yellow-brown \u0022wear and tear\u0022 pigment that accumulates with age but does not contain iron and does not stain with Prussian blue.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA carbon-containing pigment from environmental exposure\u003C/strong\u003E - Carbon pigment (anthracosis) appears black, is typically found in lung tissue from environmental exposure, and does not stain with Prussian blue.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHemosiderin accumulation can result from three main causes: (1) increased absorption of dietary iron due to hemochromatosis, (2) hemolytic anemias causing excessive red blood cell breakdown, and (3) repeated blood transfusions providing an exogenous iron load.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hemosiderin is a hemoglobin-derived golden yellow to brown pigment that is a major storage form of iron in the body.","Hemosiderin represents aggregates of ferritin micelles and accumulates when there is local or systemic excess of iron.","Systemic hemosiderosis can result from hemochromatosis, hemolytic anemias, or repeated blood transfusions."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 2; page 64-65."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78646"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20773"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78646","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78646"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-30T01:21:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-03T22:45:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13648"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95896"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11582"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Cell injury, cell death and adaptations","synonyms":[],"description":n